	&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;The oral polio vaccine was developed by&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A. Edward Jenner&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;B. Alexander Fleming&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;C. Albert Sabin&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;D. Jonas Salk&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;C.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The&lt;strong&gt; first polio vaccine was developed by &amp;#39;Jonas Salk&amp;#39; &lt;/strong&gt;and first tested in &lt;strong&gt;1952.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Albert Bruce Sabin&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;was a Polish American medical researcher known for &lt;strong&gt;developing the &amp;quot;oral polio vaccine&amp;quot;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Edward Jenner&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;was an English doctor and inventor of the &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;smallpox vaccine&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Jenner&lt;/strong&gt; is called the&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;father of immunology&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Alexander Fleming, the i&lt;strong&gt;nventor of penicillin,&lt;/strong&gt; was a biologist and pharmacologist of Scotland.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Liver.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;liver&lt;/strong&gt; secretes bile juice, which is a digesting juice.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Bile is stored in the &lt;strong&gt;gallbladder.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Bilirubin and biliverdin&lt;/strong&gt;, as well as bile salts and cholesterol,&amp;nbsp;make up bile juice.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Bile juice helps in the &lt;strong&gt;emulsification of fat.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Large fat globules are broken down into smaller globules by bile juice, making it easier for pancreatic enzymes to act on them.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The human liver is the &lt;strong&gt;largest gland in the body.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The liver is situated on the right side of the stomach.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The main function of the liver is to &lt;strong&gt;produce bile pigment.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ammonia and urea&lt;/strong&gt; are produced in the liver.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Insulin and Glucagon are the hormones secreted by the&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;pancreas.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The nutrients in digested food are absorbed from the &lt;strong&gt;small intestine.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;stomach&lt;/strong&gt; is a hollow organ that holds food while it is being mixed with stomach enzymes.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Which of the following is a nitrogen-fixing bacteria?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A. Salmonella&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;B. Rhizobium&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;C. E.coli&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;D. Pseudomonas&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;The Correct Answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 3&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt; i.e &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;B&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Salmonella&lt;/strong&gt;:

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Salmonella is a type of bacteria that makes people sick.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They were first discovered in 1885 by Dr. Daniel E. Salmon.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Salmonellosis is a disease caused by the bacteria Salmonella.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;salmonella bacteria cause foodborne illness.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is a rod-shaped bacteria or bacillus.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Rhizobium&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Rhizobium is Nitrogen fixation bacteria&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is a soil bacteria found in association with the root nodules of the leguminous plants.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The bacteria take nitrogen from the atmosphere and turn it into ammonia (NH3).&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They are frequently branched and are cylindrical in shape.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;E.coli&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Escherichia coli is abbreviated as E.coli.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is a rod-shaped bacteria.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is a type of bacteria found normally in the intestines of people and animals.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Pseudomonas&lt;/strong&gt;:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is a type of bacteria that is found commonly in the environment.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is rod-shaped, a sporogenous, and mono flagellated bacterium.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Pseudomonas infections are illnesses that are caused by the bacteria Pseudomonas.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
